Okay, but so let's start right away to talk about

36
00:01:43,759 --> 00:01:45,840
the 10 years of Assassin's Creed,

37
00:01:46,341 --> 00:01:47,922
and what I propose you today,

38
00:01:47,982 --> 00:01:50,004
just to start with a quick video,

39
00:01:50,144 --> 00:01:53,326
just to immerse ourselves a bit into the franchise.

40
00:03:09,929 --> 00:03:13,591
So yes, 10 years between basically this AC1 hoodie

41
00:03:13,651 --> 00:03:15,572
and this Origins t-shirt.

42
00:03:16,013 --> 00:03:19,475
And so the question is, how did we move from one game,

43
00:03:19,895 --> 00:03:24,217
actually a sole game, in 2007 to this massive global franchise

44
00:03:26,179 --> 00:03:26,839
of entertainment?

45
00:03:27,659 --> 00:03:30,001
I will structure this talk into three big phases.

46
00:03:30,861 --> 00:03:32,662
One about the creation of the franchise

47
00:03:32,722 --> 00:03:36,505
and finding really the recipe and our own identity.

48
00:03:37,085 --> 00:03:39,566
expanding it and finally refreshing it

49
00:03:39,987 --> 00:03:41,888
with a deeper focus on origins.

50
00:03:42,448 --> 00:03:45,530
And so if you're ready to enter the vault of Assassin's Creed,

51
00:03:45,950 --> 00:03:48,111
to enter the Animus, to deep dive into it,

52
00:03:48,191 --> 00:03:50,153
be ready because there will be a lot of things.

53
00:03:50,673 --> 00:03:53,234
And so maybe I will talk fast.

54
00:03:53,915 --> 00:03:55,596
I hope you will follow me on that.

55
00:03:55,696 --> 00:03:59,159
So let's start with the creation of Assassin's Creed.

56
00:04:00,180 --> 00:04:03,043
And I will talk about both Assassin's Creed I

57
00:04:03,183 --> 00:04:04,204
and Assassin's Creed II.

58
00:04:04,764 --> 00:04:06,326
Actually, the story starts back in 2004.

59
00:04:07,026 --> 00:04:08,868
Because as you may know already,

60
00:04:09,228 --> 00:04:11,590
the team behind Prince of Persia Sands of Time

61
00:04:11,931 --> 00:04:13,852
got the mandate to prepare for the next gen.

62
00:04:14,133 --> 00:04:16,895
And if you remember, for the oldest of you,

63
00:04:17,375 --> 00:04:19,277
next gen back in the time was Xbox 360 and PS3.

64
00:04:22,139 --> 00:04:24,701
and to also reinvent the action-adventure genre.

65
00:04:25,361 --> 00:04:27,742
And so this is really this pop next gen

66
00:04:28,182 --> 00:04:30,023
that slowly but surely morphed

67
00:04:30,564 --> 00:04:32,905
into what became Assassin's Creed.

68
00:04:33,645 --> 00:04:34,906
And with Assassin's Creed,

69
00:04:34,986 --> 00:04:37,867
when the decision was made to create this new IP,

70
00:04:38,448 --> 00:04:41,009
the idea was really to bring a more mature take,

71
00:04:41,629 --> 00:04:44,131
to come up with something

72
00:04:44,171 --> 00:04:45,971
that was really conveying the next gen.

73
00:04:47,203 --> 00:04:49,524
And here, I stop for just for a moment.

74
00:04:49,544 --> 00:04:50,945
This is the tutorial slide.

75
00:04:52,286 --> 00:04:53,886
So when you will see slides like that,

76
00:04:54,267 --> 00:04:57,248
these are actual PowerPoint slides from the dates

77
00:04:57,328 --> 00:04:57,989
that you see here.

78
00:04:58,149 --> 00:05:00,710
So this is a slide from a PowerPoint back of 2006.

79
00:05:01,170 --> 00:05:02,791
And you will see quite a lot of them.

80
00:05:03,332 --> 00:05:07,934
And so the idea was really to bring modernity, next gen,

81
00:05:07,974 --> 00:05:10,736
have something really unique and really refreshing.

82
00:05:11,396 --> 00:05:14,898
And yes, the game was set during the Middle Age,

83
00:05:15,138 --> 00:05:16,819
but not this kind of Middle Age.

84
00:05:17,339 --> 00:05:22,080
We didn't want the franchise, supposed to be a next-gen hit,

85
00:05:22,580 --> 00:05:26,961
to have this kind of treatment, very medieval,

86
00:05:27,482 --> 00:05:29,842
and so this is why some decisions were made.

87
00:05:30,542 --> 00:05:34,023
One important one was actually to have a more realistic treatment

88
00:05:34,263 --> 00:05:35,964
and to accept the M rating.

89
00:05:36,404 --> 00:05:37,704
That was not the case for POP.

90
00:05:38,024 --> 00:05:40,765
And this was a big step forward also.

91
00:05:41,785 --> 00:05:44,926
And with this realistic treatment came the present day.

92
00:05:45,606 --> 00:05:49,609
The reason behind the present day in the first place is really to create relatedness

93
00:05:50,070 --> 00:05:55,134
between the audience and the setting. Once again, yes, the game was set during the Third Crusade

94
00:05:55,794 --> 00:06:01,579
in the Middle Ages, but we wanted the overall game and the overall experience to feel

95
00:06:01,899 --> 00:06:08,124
really modern. And so with the DNA, with the animus, this was really edgy and allowing the game

96
00:06:08,544 --> 00:06:13,048
to be at the forefront of this new generation of games.

97
00:06:13,970 --> 00:06:17,131
It also came with some very strong iconic elements.

98
00:06:17,671 --> 00:06:19,911
The crest that evolved through times,

99
00:06:20,111 --> 00:06:24,632
but still remain one of the key piece of the franchise.

100
00:06:25,073 --> 00:06:28,714
A clear reference coming from the eagle, the bird of prey,

101
00:06:28,774 --> 00:06:31,774
not only about the silhouette of the hood with the beak hood,

102
00:06:32,014 --> 00:06:33,675
but also even the posing of Altair.

103
00:06:33,695 --> 00:06:36,095
And this notion of the assassin is really

104
00:06:36,115 --> 00:06:37,356
dominating the situation.

105
00:06:37,376 --> 00:06:40,497
He's overlooking the world from above,

106
00:06:40,577 --> 00:06:42,357
ready to strike whenever he wants.

107
00:06:43,577 --> 00:06:46,698
The game was also coming with the Hidden Blade, a very unique weapon.

108
00:06:47,138 --> 00:06:49,539
No other games had the same type of things.

109
00:06:49,979 --> 00:06:52,960
Very well suited for the fantasy of an assassin.

110
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:55,901
And I mentioned it already, the Animus technology

111
00:06:56,241 --> 00:07:00,863
that would allow us to link it to our 21st century audience.

112
00:07:01,743 --> 00:07:03,545
And so this was more about the treatment

113
00:07:03,825 --> 00:07:07,089
and the idea behind the rational of certain elements.

114
00:07:07,429 --> 00:07:09,812
But in terms of gameplay, it was really also entering

115
00:07:09,852 --> 00:07:10,893
the open world genre.

116
00:07:11,414 --> 00:07:15,659
Moving from a very linear, hardly level design platformer.

117
00:07:16,347 --> 00:07:22,109
to an open world game where actually these acrobatics with the parkour could be done

118
00:07:22,129 --> 00:07:30,312
and enjoyed everywhere in the city. And this was a big big step for the team. This was huge and this

119
00:07:30,552 --> 00:07:35,194
required actually new tech and this is why we developed the Envil engine.

120
00:07:35,954 --> 00:07:39,556
in order to be able to render these fully interactive cities

121
00:07:41,116 --> 00:07:43,457
that you could interact with in many, many different ways.

122
00:07:44,038 --> 00:07:45,998
All buildings were climbable, as you know.

123
00:07:46,579 --> 00:07:49,040
It was also pushing the photorealistic treatment

124
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:50,981
about characters, mostly in cinematic,

125
00:07:51,681 --> 00:07:57,743
and also the possibility to manage big crowds.

126
00:07:58,536 --> 00:08:02,639
If you remember 10 years ago, having more than 100 NPCs

127
00:08:02,939 --> 00:08:05,161
walking in the streets, that was big.

128
00:08:05,301 --> 00:08:07,923
And this was also linked to the core gameplays.

129
00:08:08,363 --> 00:08:11,125
But the thing is, and this is probably the first lesson,

130
00:08:11,405 --> 00:08:13,947
when you develop the engine at the same time

131
00:08:13,987 --> 00:08:16,789
that you develop the content, well, there is a risk.

132
00:08:17,410 --> 00:08:21,252
Builds are not stable enough, so you cannot develop properly

133
00:08:22,013 --> 00:08:23,854
gameplays and the full experience.

134
00:08:23,894 --> 00:08:25,856
So when the game hit the shelves.

135
00:08:27,325 --> 00:08:32,131
We had very good things, you know, we were the fastest selling new IP.

136
00:08:33,052 --> 00:08:36,476
So with excellent sales, the narrative really caught people,

137
00:08:36,576 --> 00:08:39,580
the Assassin fantasy, the world, the parkour, all this was good.

138
00:08:40,161 --> 00:08:44,245
But at the same time we had mixed reviews because we were lacking of things to do.

139
00:08:45,312 --> 00:08:47,514
And there was too much repetitivity.

140
00:08:47,614 --> 00:08:52,237
Some of the journalists even said, is it just a tech demo?

141
00:08:52,617 --> 00:08:57,260
And this is why I've put Assassin's Creed 2 within the

142
00:08:57,320 --> 00:08:59,001
creation section.

143
00:08:59,461 --> 00:09:02,303
Because we really needed this game to deliver the full

144
00:09:02,343 --> 00:09:03,904
promise of what Assassin's Creed was.

145
00:09:04,705 --> 00:09:08,267
So 10 years ago, actually, when I joined AC2 as a game

146
00:09:08,287 --> 00:09:10,428
designer, the mandate was really, really clear.

147
00:09:11,048 --> 00:09:13,269
It was to repeat the commercial success of AC1,

148
00:09:13,909 --> 00:09:16,531
but this time fixing all the issues it had.

149
00:09:17,591 --> 00:09:20,713
So that sounds easy, but it was quite a big challenge.

150
00:09:21,233 --> 00:09:24,175
And so what we started to do, and remember,

151
00:09:24,235 --> 00:09:25,155
these slides are from 2008.

152
00:09:27,492 --> 00:09:32,917
We analyzed thoroughly AC1, doing a post-mortem,

153
00:09:33,638 --> 00:09:36,721
looking at what people were asked to do in the game

154
00:09:36,741 --> 00:09:37,902
in terms of mission, et cetera.

155
00:09:38,002 --> 00:09:43,547
And what we realized was that actual missions of Assassin's

156
00:09:43,567 --> 00:09:46,850
Creed 1 were not asking players to do what they

157
00:09:46,870 --> 00:09:48,011
were enjoying on their own.

158
00:09:49,410 --> 00:09:53,731
So we were asking you to sit on a bench to pickpocket guys.

159
00:09:53,831 --> 00:09:55,132
Actually, when you were playing alone,

160
00:09:55,192 --> 00:09:58,212
you just like to parkour, to fight, or to blend.

161
00:09:58,832 --> 00:10:01,513
And so this was the first learning

162
00:10:02,053 --> 00:10:04,274
that helped shape Assassin's Creed 2.

163
00:10:04,594 --> 00:10:07,814
We identified our three main gameplay pillars.

164
00:10:08,494 --> 00:10:11,655
So the fight, the navigation, and the social stealth.

165
00:10:12,135 --> 00:10:15,156
And the entire game was designed around these pillars.

166
00:10:15,870 --> 00:10:18,591
So if you take the enemies, the archetypes of soldiers,

167
00:10:18,671 --> 00:10:21,151
they were challenging these three pillars.

168
00:10:21,471 --> 00:10:23,892
The three factions that you have to work with,

169
00:10:23,932 --> 00:10:25,753
that Ezio has to work with, the same,

170
00:10:26,253 --> 00:10:27,713
but supporting you on that.

171
00:10:28,053 --> 00:10:30,474
Even the type of side missions were based on that,

172
00:10:31,034 --> 00:10:34,095
so that we could actually enjoy them and support them fully.

173
00:10:34,695 --> 00:10:36,416
And so in the end, all the design loops

174
00:10:37,016 --> 00:10:41,697
were focused on actually supporting and making players

175
00:10:42,018 --> 00:10:44,878
use these pillars that were the most, the more important.

176
00:10:45,625 --> 00:10:51,390
So that was the gameplay recipe that we came up with for EC2.

177
00:10:51,790 --> 00:10:53,932
At the same time, it was also clear for us

178
00:10:54,032 --> 00:10:56,855
that the franchise was about history,

179
00:10:57,375 --> 00:11:00,078
was about making history everyone's playground.

180
00:11:00,398 --> 00:11:03,521
And from day one, we started to work with historians

181
00:11:03,921 --> 00:11:08,005
to make people immersed into living a time period.

182
00:11:08,365 --> 00:11:09,726
And so when talking about history,

183
00:11:10,407 --> 00:11:14,649
It's not about that, you know, a very old engraving of a very old man.

184
00:11:14,729 --> 00:11:19,492
The Leonardo da Vinci that you meet in the game, as you probably know, is this young,

185
00:11:19,532 --> 00:11:21,493
you know, petulant and very dynamic man.

186
00:11:22,074 --> 00:11:29,318
And with things like that, we were giving players the joy, basically the excitement

187
00:11:29,378 --> 00:11:31,099
to live history, to be part of it.

188
00:11:32,585 --> 00:11:35,966
And so while history was really the core of the experience,

189
00:11:36,807 --> 00:11:40,228
Assassin's Creed II helped us also solidify

190
00:11:40,248 --> 00:11:41,289
the rest of the narrative.

191
00:11:41,989 --> 00:11:43,390
And this wonderful onion.

192
00:11:44,390 --> 00:11:46,972
is here to show you that we kind of theorized

193
00:11:47,472 --> 00:11:48,853
the structure of our universe

194
00:11:49,474 --> 00:11:51,816
with what we called the Onion Structure,

195
00:11:52,276 --> 00:11:54,878
where it's clear that there is the video game layer,

196
00:11:55,318 --> 00:11:56,599
there is the present day layer,

197
00:11:57,140 --> 00:11:58,861
and in the present day, you enter the Animus,

198
00:11:58,901 --> 00:12:02,344
and in the Animus, you access the genetic memories

199
00:12:02,384 --> 00:12:04,385
in the past, and this is very important

200
00:12:04,425 --> 00:12:06,647
because this is solidifying everything

201
00:12:06,687 --> 00:12:08,889
within the Assassin's Creed universe.

202
00:12:09,784 --> 00:12:13,006
And so once that was solidified, we could expand

203
00:12:13,386 --> 00:12:18,090
on Desmond's story on one side, but also diving deeper

204
00:12:18,530 --> 00:12:21,032
on the mysteries with subject 16 and the puzzles

205
00:12:21,512 --> 00:12:24,695
that was actually linking it to the first civilization.

206
00:12:25,715 --> 00:12:28,978
So around the historical period, we were developing

207
00:12:28,998 --> 00:12:31,019
the present day and the first civil war.

208
00:12:31,580 --> 00:12:33,081
And this was pushing all together

209
00:12:33,441 --> 00:12:34,742
for a very strong narrative.

210
00:12:36,588 --> 00:12:39,330
This was mostly for the content, but we had only two years

211
00:12:39,410 --> 00:12:40,751
to deliver AC2.

212
00:12:40,811 --> 00:12:44,653
And so we also needed to nail the production pipeline.

213
00:12:45,394 --> 00:12:47,495
And with Assassin's Creed 2, we came up

214
00:12:47,555 --> 00:12:50,737
with some very strong design documentation,

215
00:12:50,817 --> 00:12:53,458
from the creative briefs to the FSO.

216
00:12:53,898 --> 00:12:56,500
Actually, Patrick Plourde made a talk here at GDC

217
00:12:56,540 --> 00:12:57,621
a few years ago about that.

218
00:12:58,221 --> 00:13:00,362
And also, during the end of production,

219
00:13:00,422 --> 00:13:04,344
the extensive use of playtests to secure quality of the game.

220
00:13:04,965 --> 00:13:08,706
And so this helped us also really solidify

221
00:13:08,746 --> 00:13:11,127
the way we were producing, we were developing

222
00:13:11,147 --> 00:13:12,608
Assassin's Creed.

223
00:13:13,968 --> 00:13:16,549
But back in 2008, also if you remember,

224
00:13:16,649 --> 00:13:18,710
there was a big game being released,

225
00:13:19,310 --> 00:13:22,611
spring 2008, GTA IV hit the shelves.

226
00:13:23,272 --> 00:13:26,093
And so our top management actually required us

227
00:13:26,193 --> 00:13:27,233
to beef up the game.

228
00:13:28,097 --> 00:13:31,500
to increase the scope, but giving us the means to do so.

229
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:33,641
And this was the first time we had

230
00:13:33,742 --> 00:13:35,283
multiple teams collaborating.

231
00:13:35,783 --> 00:13:41,487
So we worked with ANSI in France that was developing

232
00:13:41,648 --> 00:13:45,951
all the villa development, the villa management side.

233
00:13:46,511 --> 00:13:48,513
The newborn Singapore studio that

234
00:13:48,553 --> 00:13:51,495
helped us bringing all the secret locations,

235
00:13:51,575 --> 00:13:52,556
focusing on parkour.

236
00:13:53,615 --> 00:13:56,197
And we even created a second team in Montreal

237
00:13:56,877 --> 00:14:00,139
in charge of bringing some more exotic moments to spice up

238
00:14:00,640 --> 00:14:01,680
the overall experience.

239
00:14:01,720 --> 00:14:04,322
So think about the flying machine sequence

240
00:14:04,782 --> 00:14:07,184
or the carriage chase in the mountain.

241
00:14:07,924 --> 00:14:08,584
And so end of 2009.

242
00:14:11,581 --> 00:14:13,781
Yes, champagne, we could celebrate.

243
00:14:14,142 --> 00:14:16,182
We managed to deliver this big game,

244
00:14:16,202 --> 00:14:19,303
a quality game with a strong narrative,

245
00:14:19,363 --> 00:14:20,743
with a lot of things to do,

246
00:14:21,223 --> 00:14:23,944
with very well integrated systems,

247
00:14:24,044 --> 00:14:25,424
wonderful world to explore.

248
00:14:25,864 --> 00:14:29,245
And so we really had this certitude,

249
00:14:29,285 --> 00:14:31,045
this certainty at this moment

250
00:14:31,466 --> 00:14:33,466
that we knew what Assassin's Creed was.

251
00:14:34,066 --> 00:14:36,567
And so it was now time to move on

252
00:14:37,187 --> 00:14:39,567
and start the expansion of it, right?

253
00:14:39,627 --> 00:14:40,248
So let's see.

