00:30:59,333 --> 00:31:01,915
And so we fell again a bit in this trap

548
00:31:01,995 --> 00:31:06,077
of working a lot on the tech and not allowing

549
00:31:06,177 --> 00:31:10,159
enough the teams that create the content to actually come up

550
00:31:10,179 --> 00:31:11,040
with something new.

551
00:31:11,460 --> 00:31:14,862
And so in the end, that's the way I see it, actually.

552
00:31:15,242 --> 00:31:18,404
I think we created the perfect condition for a perfect storm.

553
00:31:18,944 --> 00:31:21,725
We had a game that was wonderful in terms of art.

554
00:31:24,008 --> 00:31:27,413
but that was not renewing enough the experience, right?

555
00:31:27,833 --> 00:31:31,839
And this map full of icons is maybe the best representation.

556
00:31:32,420 --> 00:31:35,364
At the same time, our vision about Initiate

557
00:31:35,564 --> 00:31:37,988
and an experience that was bigger than the game,

558
00:31:39,207 --> 00:31:40,608
hurt us also a lot.

559
00:31:41,048 --> 00:31:42,889
Because we came up with some design loops

560
00:31:43,370 --> 00:31:46,472
that people weren't ready and we didn't explain properly.

561
00:31:46,872 --> 00:31:49,234
And so having content locked in the game,

562
00:31:49,634 --> 00:31:51,716
you know, and that you needed asking you

563
00:31:51,756 --> 00:31:53,237
to do things on the website.

564
00:31:53,637 --> 00:31:56,319
And people got like, what's that for exactly?

565
00:31:56,899 --> 00:31:57,480
Are you kidding me?

566
00:31:57,780 --> 00:32:00,001
And so on top of that, Sunday when

567
00:32:00,021 --> 00:32:03,344
you get this kind of cherry, it hurts.

568
00:32:03,444 --> 00:32:06,206
And by the way, I need to precise that it was only

569
00:32:06,466 --> 00:32:07,787
one graphic card on PC only.

570
00:32:09,437 --> 00:32:13,299
But so, whatever, I mean, the game suffered from all this,

571
00:32:13,459 --> 00:32:17,201
even if, I mean, played today with all the fixes,

572
00:32:17,281 --> 00:32:19,182
it's still a very beautiful and very good game.

573
00:32:19,322 --> 00:32:23,425
But in short, we probably flew too close to the sun,

574
00:32:23,445 --> 00:32:25,826
too far, we were a bit overconfident.

575
00:32:26,266 --> 00:32:31,049
And this is why Syndicate had to really focus on quality.

576
00:32:31,609 --> 00:32:33,271
which the team did very, very well.

577
00:32:33,291 --> 00:32:35,493
I mean, Syndicate is a very fun game,

578
00:32:36,614 --> 00:32:39,296
well-polished, with a very interesting narrative twist

579
00:32:39,396 --> 00:32:41,638
with the Frightwins.

580
00:32:42,179 --> 00:32:45,521
And so this was basically the only thing we could do

581
00:32:45,822 --> 00:32:48,964
with Syndicate to actually solidify

582
00:32:50,045 --> 00:32:52,548
the experience that we knew how to do.

583
00:32:53,609 --> 00:32:57,653
But we also knew it was time, this time, for a strong,

584
00:32:57,693 --> 00:32:59,314
and for a big, big refresh.

585
00:33:00,055 --> 00:33:04,238
And when I talk about refresh, I never talk about reboot.

586
00:33:04,559 --> 00:33:07,561
Actually, we had tons of discussions internally,

587
00:33:08,082 --> 00:33:11,004
and I always fought to say refresh more than reboot.

588
00:33:11,705 --> 00:33:14,928
Because at the same time, I felt it was super important

589
00:33:14,948 --> 00:33:16,729
to respect our franchise.

590
00:33:16,969 --> 00:33:19,151
We know Assassin's Creed, we own it.

591
00:33:20,032 --> 00:33:23,714
We are the only ones that can adapt it without betraying it.

592
00:33:24,194 --> 00:33:27,596
So the two aspects are key in my mind.

593
00:33:28,597 --> 00:33:31,098
And let's start with the refresh of the experience.

594
00:33:31,458 --> 00:33:33,820
This was the key thing.

595
00:33:34,780 --> 00:33:37,462
At first, we needed clear priorities.

596
00:33:38,102 --> 00:33:40,984
So in 2014, this is a team meeting slide.

597
00:33:41,684 --> 00:33:45,826
The four big direction, basically, I gave to the team

598
00:33:45,866 --> 00:33:48,808
was, OK, we need to show that we master open world creation.

599
00:33:50,251 --> 00:33:53,792
We need to find a better, if not perfect, balance

600
00:33:54,092 --> 00:33:56,993
between the story and player's agency, be less hand-holding.

601
00:33:58,034 --> 00:34:01,295
We need to be a not-skippable episode in the AC universe

602
00:34:01,675 --> 00:34:05,056
and to remain a connected game, even if without co-op.

603
00:34:05,476 --> 00:34:09,078
We need to show that being part of the community

604
00:34:09,478 --> 00:34:11,979
brings value to your overall experience.

605
00:34:12,659 --> 00:34:14,360
We're not a competitive franchise,

606
00:34:14,800 --> 00:34:16,701
but the community is very, very strong,

607
00:34:17,141 --> 00:34:18,121
and we need to leverage that.

608
00:34:18,962 --> 00:34:26,067
And so the idea behind modernizing AC was really to have the focus in terms of fluidity and player's freedom.

609
00:34:26,667 --> 00:34:28,909
That was key message given to the team.

610
00:34:29,449 --> 00:34:35,053
It's not about us, it's about the players and they want to be free, they want to do what they want.

611
00:34:36,454 --> 00:34:41,418
And if needed, we need to adapt ourselves, our tools, our cultures.

612
00:34:42,663 --> 00:34:46,526
And so making a modern Assassin's Creed

613
00:34:46,546 --> 00:34:48,907
was really about being more systemic,

614
00:34:49,668 --> 00:34:52,330
more player-friendly, more connected,

615
00:34:52,550 --> 00:34:55,832
and also, like I said, having a modernized pipeline.

616
00:34:56,493 --> 00:34:58,594
This is why we came up with this

617
00:34:59,154 --> 00:35:00,916
archipelago structure of the world.

618
00:35:01,767 --> 00:35:06,989
So if you remember, this is basically the core team of Origins is the one that delivered

619
00:35:07,009 --> 00:35:07,530
Black Flag.

620
00:35:07,970 --> 00:35:13,752
And so we came up with this structure of the world where procedural tools would allow us

621
00:35:13,832 --> 00:35:20,334
to create a lot of terrain, of ground, but where artists and level design were still

622
00:35:20,475 --> 00:35:27,017
owner of location, precise locations to really have high quality and crafted locations.

623
00:35:28,161 --> 00:35:30,223
At the same time, even with the eagle,

624
00:35:30,243 --> 00:35:33,225
so you see this is a prototype from the end of 2014.

625
00:35:33,345 --> 00:35:37,468
With the eagle, the intention was to redefine

626
00:35:37,488 --> 00:35:39,750
the way we understand the world,

627
00:35:40,170 --> 00:35:41,551
the way we interact with it,

628
00:35:42,572 --> 00:35:44,053
and the way we see it living.

629
00:35:44,133 --> 00:35:45,515
Remember, living and breathing world,

630
00:35:45,555 --> 00:35:47,036
we said that for 10 years now,

631
00:35:47,116 --> 00:35:49,558
but this had to be true more than ever.

632
00:35:51,139 --> 00:35:52,820
So it's good to have a big world,

633
00:35:53,701 --> 00:35:55,843
but we needed to feel it in a meaningful way.

634
00:35:56,615 --> 00:35:59,377
And so this is why we came up with this meta AI,

635
00:35:59,578 --> 00:36:00,638
the global AI.

636
00:36:01,059 --> 00:36:04,621
Something, think about an RTS AI

637
00:36:05,342 --> 00:36:07,083
set on top of an open world game

638
00:36:07,503 --> 00:36:09,185
where people would have their agenda

639
00:36:09,385 --> 00:36:11,586
and bringing credibility to the world

640
00:36:12,127 --> 00:36:14,508
while letting systems work all together

641
00:36:15,189 --> 00:36:18,291
and interact together to create emerging situations

642
00:36:18,351 --> 00:36:20,933
that we would not have predicted.

643
00:36:21,614 --> 00:36:24,937
And this was a very important step forward

644
00:36:24,997 --> 00:36:26,638
because the teams needed to understand

645
00:36:26,678 --> 00:36:28,780
that we needed to work more on situations

646
00:36:29,361 --> 00:36:32,043
and create good conditions of things to happen

647
00:36:32,243 --> 00:36:35,566
rather than scenarios that need to unfold

648
00:36:35,706 --> 00:36:37,308
in that specific sequence.

649
00:36:38,645 --> 00:36:41,806
And obviously, one of the big topic was also the fight,

650
00:36:42,446 --> 00:36:45,847
where we moved from animation paired system,

651
00:36:46,147 --> 00:36:49,428
paired animation system, sorry, to a hitbox system.

652
00:36:49,948 --> 00:36:52,228
And this was meant to really bring a fight

653
00:36:52,268 --> 00:36:54,249
that was more challenging, that was deeper,

654
00:36:54,369 --> 00:36:58,050
with meaningful weapons, being more reactive also,

655
00:36:58,530 --> 00:37:00,130
and way more modern.

656
00:37:00,730 --> 00:37:03,591
And this was coming also with, as you can see,

657
00:37:03,631 --> 00:37:04,872
transition animation shorter.

658
00:37:04,912 --> 00:37:06,772
Animation won't always match perfectly.

659
00:37:07,432 --> 00:37:09,233
That's OK from a player's perspective.

660
00:37:09,694 --> 00:37:12,255
But some of the team was struggling with that.

661
00:37:12,976 --> 00:37:15,237
And so in the end, we had to keep

662
00:37:15,277 --> 00:37:19,880
repeating that it was a cultural shift for the developers

663
00:37:20,120 --> 00:37:21,681
as much as a technological one.

664
00:37:22,241 --> 00:37:23,382
This was really important.

665
00:37:23,842 --> 00:37:25,743
And we kept repeating that to the team.

666
00:37:25,783 --> 00:37:28,405
We should focus on the experience and not

667
00:37:28,425 --> 00:37:29,845
the scripting or hard coding.

668
00:37:30,646 --> 00:37:32,467
Players don't care about our code.

669
00:37:32,707 --> 00:37:34,828
They just care about their experience.

670
00:37:35,885 --> 00:37:40,066
And so we needed to understand that losing a bit of control

671
00:37:40,686 --> 00:37:43,046
would bring more fun to the players

672
00:37:43,527 --> 00:37:44,887
rather than creating issues.

673
00:37:44,967 --> 00:37:47,287
And I mean, I had people came to me saying,

674
00:37:47,307 --> 00:37:49,888
do you really want to deliver a crappy game?

675
00:37:50,208 --> 00:37:50,608
I said, no.

676
00:37:51,228 --> 00:37:52,029
It won't be the same.

677
00:37:52,049 --> 00:37:53,149
It will be fun.

678
00:37:54,469 --> 00:37:58,270
And so, yeah, I called that operation losing the tie.

679
00:37:59,911 --> 00:38:04,052
Same badass and quality, but can we just breathe a bit more?

680
00:38:05,358 --> 00:38:07,179
more open, more fluid, and more modern.

681
00:38:07,999 --> 00:38:08,739
So that was the goal.

682
00:38:09,840 --> 00:38:11,220
But that was not an easy road.

683
00:38:11,901 --> 00:38:15,982
And so if you want to come by Montreal, work with us,

684
00:38:17,603 --> 00:38:18,283
be prepared.

685
00:38:18,363 --> 00:38:20,164
This is the kind of streets we have.

686
00:38:23,425 --> 00:38:24,886
But the balance was hard to find.

687
00:38:26,580 --> 00:38:30,781
So again, 2016, we had to, I mean, it was a constant,

688
00:38:30,801 --> 00:38:34,561
you know, repeat process to explain that, for example,

689
00:38:34,622 --> 00:38:37,422
the setting, the envelope of the experience,

690
00:38:37,802 --> 00:38:39,442
so the time period, the world, the stories,

691
00:38:39,743 --> 00:38:40,703
we knew how to do that.

692
00:38:41,323 --> 00:38:43,163
We did it already many times.

693
00:38:43,883 --> 00:38:46,124
But all the structure of the experience,

694
00:38:46,664 --> 00:38:47,704
a lot of that was new.

695
00:38:48,404 --> 00:38:50,245
We're literally moving from, you know,

696
00:38:50,285 --> 00:38:52,805
a gas engine to electrical car.

697
00:38:53,700 --> 00:38:57,263
And this is not easy.

698
00:38:57,303 --> 00:38:59,784
We were out of our comfort zone.

699
00:39:00,765 --> 00:39:04,887
So at some point, we had teams not liking each other.

700
00:39:05,956 --> 00:39:09,559
I mean, the guys in charge of all the systemic aspects were coming to us and say,

701
00:39:10,059 --> 00:39:14,782
okay, these people, they want to tell stories and they want to control the systems.

702
00:39:15,363 --> 00:39:18,585
How are we supposed to do systemic things if you want to control them?

703
00:39:19,045 --> 00:39:21,287
And on the other side, the narrative team was coming and saying,

704
00:39:21,647 --> 00:39:24,009
how are we supposed to tell stories if they want, you know,

705
00:39:24,209 --> 00:39:27,771
they don't want less to take control of the systems?

706
00:39:28,412 --> 00:39:31,634
So we had these tensions, but in the end it turned well.

707
00:39:32,324 --> 00:39:35,525
I think we all respect each other.

708
00:39:35,665 --> 00:39:38,906
We are all seasoned developers.

709
00:39:39,746 --> 00:39:40,946
And we found this balance.

710
00:39:41,146 --> 00:39:43,347
Remember the first, the objective, second objective

711
00:39:43,467 --> 00:39:46,648
balance between a narrative and player's agency?

712
00:39:47,128 --> 00:39:49,868
Where with this quest structure, we

713
00:39:49,888 --> 00:39:52,489
would have narratives, meaningful narratives,

714
00:39:52,569 --> 00:39:56,210
but using the systems, not directing every single bit

715
00:39:56,530 --> 00:39:57,410
of each mission.

716
00:39:58,316 --> 00:40:00,657
And so these were really the big, big things

717
00:40:00,697 --> 00:40:01,678
that we need to change.

718
00:40:02,058 --> 00:40:05,180
But at the same time, every day, every week, every month,

719
00:40:05,580 --> 00:40:08,102
we had to ask ourselves, what should we keep?

720
00:40:08,782 --> 00:40:09,663
What should we change?

721
00:40:10,163 --> 00:40:12,064
For example, think about the climbing.

722
00:40:12,825 --> 00:40:14,726
We knew that set in ancient Egypt,

723
00:40:15,146 --> 00:40:16,527
climbing were less prominent.

724
00:40:16,627 --> 00:40:18,809
I mean, we have less buildings, that's for sure.

725
00:40:19,169 --> 00:40:21,610
So how do we keep this verticality

726
00:40:21,831 --> 00:40:23,271
that is really needed for AC?

727
00:40:24,124 --> 00:40:26,347
Well, we want the navigation, we want the climbing

728
00:40:26,787 --> 00:40:28,188
to be available on all cliffs,

729
00:40:28,709 --> 00:40:30,751
so that we could have set up in camps,

730
00:40:31,091 --> 00:40:33,394
you know, in caves, using the mountains

731
00:40:33,914 --> 00:40:35,456
as a level design element.

732
00:40:37,118 --> 00:40:39,800
I like this example first because it's a very old video,

733
00:40:39,840 --> 00:40:41,382
as you can see the world here,

734
00:40:42,143 --> 00:40:44,906
but it's about the reach high points, you know,

735
00:40:44,966 --> 00:40:45,506
the way points.

736
00:40:46,393 --> 00:40:47,293
What do we do with that?

737
00:40:47,673 --> 00:40:48,574
This is key.

738
00:40:48,634 --> 00:40:50,355
I mean, it's iconic of Assassin's Creed.

739
00:40:50,415 --> 00:40:51,495
You need to climb something,

740
00:40:51,535 --> 00:40:53,896
you dominate the world of these wonderful vistas,

741
00:40:54,356 --> 00:40:56,197
and then it ends up with the leap of faith.

742
00:40:56,977 --> 00:40:58,958
Which is, I mean, these three elements

743
00:40:59,178 --> 00:41:01,739
are almost defining what Assassin's Creed is.

744
00:41:02,866 --> 00:41:04,327
So do we keep it or not?

745
00:41:05,167 --> 00:41:07,328
If we keep it, it makes sense.

746
00:41:08,028 --> 00:41:12,970
But at the same time, we need to remove the link between that

747
00:41:13,550 --> 00:41:14,870
and the discovery of the world.

748
00:41:15,091 --> 00:41:18,632
Because this was feeling very old, very the same way.

749
00:41:18,972 --> 00:41:20,713
So this is why we kept the feature,

750
00:41:21,253 --> 00:41:23,073
but we changed its utility.

751
00:41:23,514 --> 00:41:26,275
You don't unfog the map anymore with that.

752
00:41:27,675 --> 00:41:30,876
We asked ourselves a lot about social self.

753
00:41:31,665 --> 00:41:34,047
Does it make sense for Bayek to blend in groups?

754
00:41:34,988 --> 00:41:38,271
While in the narrative side, he's not per se an assassin,

755
00:41:38,311 --> 00:41:40,413
he's more a proto-assassin, more of a warrior.

756
00:41:40,753 --> 00:41:43,796
Doesn't make any real sense to have him with big axes,

757
00:41:43,856 --> 00:41:46,778
you know, hiding among civilians.

758
00:41:46,939 --> 00:41:50,362
So we decided to focus instead on environmental stealth.

759
00:41:51,162 --> 00:41:53,044
This is why the hidden blade, for example,

760
00:41:53,144 --> 00:41:55,866
that was the nuclear weapon of assassins,

761
00:41:56,407 --> 00:41:59,509
and that was preventing us from having a good progression.

762
00:42:00,362 --> 00:42:06,746
because you don't care about being level 40 if with one hit with the blade you can kill anybody.

763
00:42:07,306 --> 00:42:11,149
So we needed to accept that the blade would need to be upgraded.

764
00:42:11,169 --> 00:42:16,172
And even the chests. We have quite a lot of chests still.

765
00:42:16,492 --> 00:42:19,013
But do we want the map to be filled with this type of icons?

766
00:42:19,734 --> 00:42:21,795
When we can actually just change the icon?

767
00:42:22,682 --> 00:42:28,887
and having an icon better suited for the setting

768
00:42:29,128 --> 00:42:32,911
and removing this reference to the old chest formula.

769
00:42:33,932 --> 00:42:36,094
And so this was the way we worked

770
00:42:36,214 --> 00:42:37,475
to refresh the experience.

771
00:42:37,855 --> 00:42:39,297
At the same time, like I was saying,

772
00:42:39,677 --> 00:42:43,681
we needed to refresh and to respect our identity.

773
00:42:44,723 --> 00:42:48,685
And what I mean is that we tried to create as many references

774
00:42:49,765 --> 00:42:54,186
and connection between origins and past games.

775
00:42:55,286 --> 00:42:58,227
For example, the eagle, obviously, was important.

776
00:42:58,887 --> 00:43:00,628
It's key to the franchise.

777
00:43:00,648 --> 00:43:02,988
Think about Assassin's Creed 1 part.

778
00:43:04,329 --> 00:43:07,610
Having the cut finger also to hold the blade was important.

779
00:43:08,090 --> 00:43:10,592
And even in the posing of Altair and marketing assets,

780
00:43:10,672 --> 00:43:12,453
even if we never juxtaposed the two,

781
00:43:12,813 --> 00:43:15,475
there was this reminiscence of AC1.

782
00:43:16,036 --> 00:43:19,418
The use of artifacts also was the same.

783
00:43:19,678 --> 00:43:22,240
Whereas the first game set prior to AC1,

784
00:43:23,441 --> 00:43:25,342
but we didn't want to fall into this

785
00:43:25,883 --> 00:43:28,745
totally crazy fantasy of Egypt.

786
00:43:29,445 --> 00:43:32,948
So we kept that low profile basically.

787
00:43:33,429 --> 00:43:35,891
But the way we treated the first Siv drawings

788
00:43:36,311 --> 00:43:38,713
was the exact same, right?

789
00:43:38,914 --> 00:43:40,855
This is actually the exact, I mean,

790
00:43:40,895 --> 00:43:42,777
that's the same artist that did both.

791
00:43:44,263 --> 00:43:45,844
With Aya, sorry for the spoiler,

792
00:43:45,944 --> 00:43:48,686
but I assume that you know everything I'm talking about.

793
00:43:49,486 --> 00:43:52,969
In AC2, we had Amunet in the vault, right?

794
00:43:53,169 --> 00:43:57,072
Famous Egyptian assassin, where we reveal that's Aya.

795
00:43:57,732 --> 00:43:59,533
And in the DLC, The Hidden Ones,

796
00:43:59,834 --> 00:44:02,876
her costume is directly inspired from the vault of AC2.

797
00:44:03,176 --> 00:44:05,378
So you see creating references, loops like that,

798
00:44:05,838 --> 00:44:08,460
even with this final scene echoing

799
00:44:08,480 --> 00:44:10,641
the trailer of Assassin's Creed 1.

800
00:44:11,941 --> 00:44:14,264
And so with these little details,

801
00:44:15,526 --> 00:44:20,433
I think we managed to always secure, especially our fans,

802
00:44:20,873 --> 00:44:24,438
that this was a true Assassin's Creed game.

803
00:44:25,079 --> 00:44:26,662
And this was also true with the present day.

804
00:44:27,931 --> 00:44:33,173
We are back with the formula with the third person character, introducing Leila, because

805
00:44:33,193 --> 00:44:38,736
we think this formula has a lot to bring in terms of narrative, and it's better understood.

806
00:44:39,076 --> 00:44:41,917
But even with that, we can create connections.

807
00:44:43,078 --> 00:44:51,202
William is Desmond's father, and if you look into our computer, you have tons of references

808
00:44:51,242 --> 00:44:52,843
to other games and the movies.

809
00:44:54,123 --> 00:44:54,403
And so...

810
00:44:55,785 --> 00:45:00,208
That's the way we refresh and respect Assassin's Creed.

811
00:45:01,089 --> 00:45:03,971
In a few words, basically I would have to say

812
00:45:04,011 --> 00:45:05,672
that know your brand first.

813
00:45:05,972 --> 00:45:09,014
If you don't want people to screw it, to dilute it,

814
00:45:09,535 --> 00:45:12,357
to say or do things that are not supposed to be done,

815
00:45:12,997 --> 00:45:15,959
know it and communicate it, right?

816
00:45:16,239 --> 00:45:17,720
Think about the Bibles, et cetera.

817
00:45:18,320 --> 00:45:21,481
In terms of gameplay, you need to clearly identify your strengths.

818
00:45:22,041 --> 00:45:26,602
What are the things, the features that make your game shine,

819
00:45:26,922 --> 00:45:29,803
so that you can focus on it and try to disperse yourself.

820
00:45:30,423 --> 00:45:33,184
But at the same time, don't hesitate to grow your teams.

821
00:45:33,864 --> 00:45:37,104
This growth of Assassin's Creed during the last decade

822
00:45:37,144 --> 00:45:40,125
would not have been possible without other studios all around the world.

823
00:45:40,605 --> 00:45:44,166
If we were too protective, this wouldn't work.

824
00:45:44,586 --> 00:45:46,646
The same with external teams.

825
00:45:47,757 --> 00:45:50,380
comics, movies, et cetera.

826
00:45:50,940 --> 00:45:52,842
And the last lesson I would encourage you

827
00:45:52,882 --> 00:45:54,103
is to listen to your audience.

828
00:45:55,384 --> 00:45:56,605
We really try to do it.

829
00:45:57,386 --> 00:46:00,449
With this, you know, Initiates, Global Hub, et cetera,

830
00:46:00,489 --> 00:46:01,930
we went probably a bit too far.

831
00:46:02,351 --> 00:46:06,374
But in general, I mean, you need to listen to your audience,

832
00:46:06,534 --> 00:46:07,896
not only the hardcore fans.

833
00:46:09,037 --> 00:46:10,098
That's the advice I would say.

834
00:46:10,658 --> 00:46:13,061
So just to finish finish, it's actually quite simple.

835
00:46:13,121 --> 00:46:14,222
I like this slide.

836
00:46:14,943 --> 00:46:18,427
For me, it's creation in general, conception in general,

837
00:46:18,888 --> 00:46:22,772
developing games or whatever, is all about this Taishi

838
00:46:22,812 --> 00:46:24,694
mentality, being solid.

839
00:46:25,535 --> 00:46:26,536
You know what you want to do.

840
00:46:27,521 --> 00:46:29,243
At the same time, remaining flexible,

841
00:46:29,463 --> 00:46:32,906
you need to be able to adapt to opportunities or issues

842
00:46:33,586 --> 00:46:35,848
and remain open so that you can work with others

843
00:46:35,929 --> 00:46:39,852
that will bring you solutions, ideas, et cetera.

844
00:46:40,372 --> 00:46:45,077
So it's this constant flux between solidity,

845
00:46:45,157 --> 00:46:48,340
not stiffness, and flexibility.

846
00:46:49,481 --> 00:46:50,321
And that's it for me today.

847
00:46:50,582 --> 00:46:51,122
Thank you very much.

848
00:47:01,113 --> 00:47:04,054
So I think we have time for some questions.

849
00:47:04,234 --> 00:47:05,214
You can come to the mic.

